entry.title: Create autofill field promo controller & view
entry.content:
These classes are responsible for showing and hiding IPH bubbles which

need to be attached directly to DOM elements.



The controller will be owned (in a future CL) by the autofill client.

The controller manages hiding and showing the view.



The view is actually an invisible view which completely covers the

bottom boundary of the element. The IPH is then anchored to this view.

This gives the visual impression that the IPH is anchored to the DOM

element.



This code can be used to display multiple IPH's. For every IPH, a new

controller has to be created. The `ElementIdentifier` passed to the

controller dictates which IPH will be shown.

entry.title: [css-functions] Add implicit calc() as needed.
entry.content:
When resolving a function argument or return value to a given type,

add calc() around it if the type is amenable to it (i.e., is a

numeric type). This makes them much more ergonomic to write, e.g.

instead of writing



@return calc(--foo(calc(arg(--x) * 2)) + 3);



you can write



@return --foo(arg(--x) * 2) + 3;



which is much easier to read.



Since this would leave a stray calc() (e.g. calc(10)) on the return

value if we added it to a non-registered or universal-syntax custom

property, we now also resolve the resulting value against the element

as if it were against a registered custom property of the given type.

This will then also resolve units when possible, further simplifying

the expression.

entry.title: [css-functions] Initial prototype of CSS functions.
entry.content:
This is a very early prototype of user-defined CSS functions, based on

our position paper and behind the flag CSSFunctions. This is mainly

to get experience with the syntax and implementation. It is not suitable

for production use. Among the more important missing parts:



- There is no support for local variables.

- There is no cycle detection (so any attempt at recursion will

trivially crash the renderer).

- The Iverson bracket functions are not supported yet, so any @media

queries or similar will need to be made using helper custom

properties (on :root or similar).

- Style is not properly updated if a @function changes (i.e.,

the stylesheet is replaced)



There is also no support for @function in cascade layers, or in CSSOM.



The syntax may change at any time.

entry.title: Fix dangling pointers in win_system_signals_service_unittest.cc.
entry.content:
The constructor for the unittest (`WinSystemSignalsServiceTest`),

creates 3 sub-objects owned by unique_ptrs and moves them to

`win_system_signals_service_`. It holds on to the sub-objects via raw_ptr.



This causes dangling pointer detection to fire during test destruction

as the ordering of the member variables (in the unittest) causes the

owning object to be destroyed first (thus making the sub-objects

dangling -- for an instant).



Re-ordering the raw_ptr sub-objects such that they are destroyed first

avoids this problem.

entry.title: Annotate existing dangling pointers to re-enable DPD [5/N]
entry.content:
Context:

--------

The DanglingPointerDetector has been disabled today in:

https://crrev.com/c/5288053



The cause was a bug in MiracleObject, causing memory leak for all the

targeted objects: RenderFrameHost, View, BrowserContext, ... This

prevented the DanglingPointerDetector to be enforced. It also caused a

memory regression on M122 beta.



It had to be reverted, but it couldn't because of the dangling pointers

we missed. So, the DanglingPointerDetector had to be disabled too to

allow cherry-picking the revert to beta.



We must enable it as soon as possible: It is easier to block developers

against the CQ than fixing issues after they have been merged. Without

it, developers are missing ~15 new dangling pointers every day.



This patch:

-----------



This patch annotate the dangling pointers we missed while MiracleObject

was enabled.



The goal is to allow a follow-up to enable the

DanglingPointerDetector again.

entry.title: [bfcache] Stop blocking on DrainedAsBytesConsumer
entry.content:
This CL introduces a flag to stop evicting bfcache entry on datapipe

drained as bytes consumer.

entry.title: Remove old OOF fragmentation spanner-awareness code.
entry.content:
This was needed back when OOFs didn't affect column balancing. We would

in some cases have to manually create additional fragmentainers when

starting layout of an OOF (with a sufficiently large block-offset)

*after* the spanner, even though the OOF was defined before the spanner.

We no longer do that, now that OOFs affect column balancing.



The code that's now removed had no effect (as far as I can tell) in

non-nested multicol, since we always make room for OOFs before the

spanner. However, it did do something in nested multicol with spanners,

because we'll fail to make enough room for OOFs in cases where they

would cross an outer fragmentainer boundary. What this code did was

wrong in such cases anyway. It would push additional fragmentainers

below the spanner, and not set the right block-size, resulting in

overflowing the outer fragmentation context in the block direction. By

removing this code, we'll now just create additional fragmentainers at

the same block-offset as the last one, progressing in the inline

direction. This is the best we can do (and what we did in all other

cases, anyway), since we don't support creation of additional outer

fragmentainers for OOFs.



Two unit tests have to be updated, because of the above. One of them now

behave correctly, while the other one still isn't quite there. Add a web

test for it as well.



By removing this code, UpdatedFragmentainerOffset() ended up only adding

fragmentainer_progression, if it was a new fragment. Just remove the

function and do the job at the call site instead.



In LayoutOOFsInFragmentainer(), if we find the last fragmentainer

*before* calling GetFragmentainerConstraintSpace(), we won't have to do

the same job in there, since GetFragmentainerConstraintSpace() no longer

needs to know whether it's a new fragmentainer or not.



This doesn't really fix crbug.com/40775119 , but it does improve the

rendering of the demo there.



Bug: 40775119

entry.title: fetch_request_window_id is set only when ServiceWorkerObjectHost exists
entry.content:
This CL adds a speculative fix to crbug.com/324559079.



`ServiceWorkerProviderContext::SetController()` hits CHECK(controller_)

sometimes. This CHECK runs when

`controller_info->fetch_request_window_id` exists, and the |controller_|

comes from `controller_info->object_info` [1].



|fetch_request_window_id| is set in the browser side,

ServiceWorkerContainerHost::CreateControllerServiceWorkerInfo() [2].

|fetch_request_window_id| is always set as far as controller exists and

the value is not null. However, |object_info| is set only when

`GetOrCreateServiceWorkerObjectHost()` returns the

ServiceWorkerObjectHost weakptr, and the method could return nullptr [3].



So, if |fetch_request_window_id| is set, and

GetOrCreateServiceWorkerObjectHost() is failed, then hits CHECK error.



After this CL, `CreateControllerServiceWorkerInfo()`, which sets

|fetch_request_window_id|, is called only when both |controller_| and

|context_| are not null. Because `GetOrCreateServiceWorkerObjectHost()`

returns null if |context_| is null, in that case we should treat is as

no controller case.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/renderer/service_worker/service_worker_provider_context.cc;l=384

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/service_worker/service_worker_container_host.cc;l=686

[3] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/service_worker/service_worker_container_host.cc;l=721-725

entry.title: [office] serialise uploads
entry.content:
Every upload handler creates a separate CopyOrMoveIOTask for each file,

which does its own conflict resolution. This may result in tasks

resolving to the same destination file, and multiple source files being

copied to the same destination, losing one of the files.



In the long run we should have a single CopyOrMoveIOTask here, but

serialising uploads is the least invasive change at this point.

entry.title: Make MetricsServicesManagerClient the owner of SyntheticTrialRegistry.
entry.content:
With this change VariationsService will have a pointer to the SyntheticTrialRegistry, through which trials that branch within VariationsService can be registered (e.g. the limited entropy synthetic trial).



Currently, SyntheticTrialRegistry is owned by MetricsServiceClient, and is accessible from MetricsService. Since VariationsService is instantiated separately from MetricsService, to reach for SyntheticTrialRegistry, VariationsService will have to reach for g_browser_process->metrics_service(). However this requires g_browser_process to be initialized, which is not guaranteed when instantiating VariationsService.



To resolve this issue, the ownership of SyntheticTrialRegistry is lifted out of MetricsServiceClient, and is given to its owner, MetricsServicesManagerClient, which is also the owner of VariationsService. This way, both MetricsService and VariationsService will share the same instance of SyntheticTrialRegistry at instantiation.



LimitedEntropySyntheticTrial will be accessing SyntheticTrialRegistry from within VariationsService. A previous design added VariationsServiceClient::RegisterLimitedEntropySyntheticTrial for this purpose, but this approach will crash the client because of a null g_browser_process (as explained above). For this reason this change also removes VariationsServiceClient::RegisterLimitedEntropySyntheticTrial.

entry.title: Allow rvalue arrays in as_byte_span, and type-deduce rvalue arrays
entry.content:
Arrays can come in rvalue form as for example `{1, 2, 3}` which

resolves to an `int (&&)[3]` type, and which binds to

`const int (&)[3]` but not `int (&)[3]`.



span thus can be constructed from an rvalue array

but as_byte_span() which returns a span over `const uint8_t` was

expecting a mutable array input, which prevented the use of an

rvalue. Adjust as_byte_span() to match the behaviour of the span()

constructor.



span() also allows type deduction for building a span from an

lvalue array, but it was missed for an rvalue array. Fix this by

allowing `span` to be deduced from a `const T (&)[N]`

type, which then calls the ctor that already exists.

entry.title: Improved page colors calculation on initialization
entry.content:
This CL improves the way page colors is calculated upon initialization.

Previously, PageColors::Init() used PageColors::OnPageColorsChanged(),

which did not ensure that the initial calculation considered the

preferred contrast state. Therefore, this CL replaces

OnPageColorsChanged() with PageColors::OnPreferredContrastChanged(),

which ends up calling OnPageColorsChanged() after accounting for the

user’s contrast preference.
